metadata.name: Organicon, variation 00 - special edition #490
metadata.description:
Thank you!

Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
One of 640 special edition generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation 00 is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: Acid Quilt #368
metadata.description:
This is an abstract work. There is no true or correct orientation.

Inspired by repeater patterns, tiles, tessellations, and quilts. Not as goofy as the Collage of Collage set but still some goofiness to it. This collage set is made up of layers sketched on a really old ipad. 

The project does not have a repeater functions built in, just produces the single base unit. My hope is that the output be used on a larger canvas and repeated, tiled, or tessellated. Some outputs might could look good in a quilt. 

These online tools (as of Feb 2022) are easy to use for making tiles. Windows also makes it easy to tile, as does Photoshop:
- https://www.imgonline.com.ua/eng/check-texture-tiling.php
- https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/gdiplus/-gdiplus-tiling-a-shape-with-an-image-use
- https://prinfab.com/printed-fabric?r2=magic

(^This^ is very much not a best practice, including links in this description that might not exist in the future)

There are more than 1.3 billion possible combos!

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: Proxima #170
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: R√™ve em Nuvens #58
metadata.description:
Even though sometimes our horizon seems to be obscured by problems and difficulties, the weather is always clear above the clouds.

"R√™ves em Nuvens", a mixture of French and Portuguese words meaning "Dreams in the clouds", is intended to be a message of hope and encouragement for all those who, at some point, have seen their perspectives disappear. They are still there, the stars and the sky are only hidden behind clouds.

Born from a two-month collaboration between Omar Lobato and Estienne, "R√™ve em Nuvens" uses noise assemblages to reproduce a cloudy sky, sometimes at night under a full moon, during a late afternoon or a sunny day. 

The colors, shape, texture and turbulence of the clouds are all variations that will give this series a style that can be both realistic and fantastic.

Although the parameters are attached to the hash of each edition, certain options are offered in order to be able to generate the image in the style that suits you best, whether for display on screen, or for printing:

Press the [1] key to toggle the noise effect
Press the [2] key to toggle the stucco texture
Press the [3] key to toggle the lines texture

Press the [S] key to save a 4K image in PNG format

Add "?size=xxx" at the end of the url to generate an image of xxx pixels

Authors: Omar Lobato & Estienne
May 2022

metadata.name: Seasons #222
metadata.description:
Seasons depicts monolithic mountains and calm seas scattered with unnatural elements.
The color palettes explore the colors of natural landscapes through different times of year.

To ease browser load, the images are paused by default.
Hitting 'p' will toggle a subtle animation.
Hitting 't' will toggle between the day and night palette for the image.
On mobile the resolution is reduced and the image is always paused to ease the load on the device.

Generative images by 0x3739
twitter.com/0x3739
library: twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library
license: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Tested and functioning correctly on Google Chrome version 100.0.4896.88 on Windows desktop and Android mobile device.

The work is rendered in webgl as a fragment shader.
Setting parameters in the javascript portion of the script generates a different fragment shader for each iteration.

Interactions
'-' to zoom in.
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'z' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to A4/A3/A2/A1 format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
'q' to change the aspect ratio to portrait.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
'p' to pause the animation the image.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the margins on the image.
'm' to toggle the mountains in the image.
'c' to toggle the clouds in the image.
'g' to toggle the grid in the image.
'd' to toggle the dirt speckles in the image.
'n' to toggle the noise in the image.
'j' to toggle the jitter in the image.
'v' to toggle all vintage effects in the image.
'1' to toggle the stars in the image.
'2' to toggle the moons in the image.
'3' to toggle the black squares in the image.
'4' to toggle the white squares in the image.
'5' to toggle the primary color squares in the image.
'6' to toggle the secundary color squares in the image.
'7' to toggle the colour correction in the image.
'8' to toggle the sea in the image.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash. 
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.

metadata.name: Expresi√≥n Urbanistica #53
metadata.description:
"Expresi√≥n Urbanistica" is a collection inspired by urban textures and development. The original idea came from the landscape of my city which is vibrant and sometimes soft in terms of color. 

For me "Expresi√≥n Urbanistica" is the feeling that I get each time that I look through my window, each time that I get out of my house, and each time I watch a sunset through my balcony.
